tr.td:
Patient comes in today for evaluation of low back pain. He states that it occurs in both of his buttocks and travels up into his back. He has to sit on the hard surface for relief. He states that this is been ongoing since 1999. He does not remember whether he has had injections or not but he is in a pain management clinic. He takes oxycodone for pain relief. His pain is a constant 10 out of 10 described as sharp, stabbing, burning with stiffness. It is worse in all activity except for lying down that does improve it somewhat. He reports nocturnal disturbance as well.
Past Medical History, Family History, Personal and Social History and Review of Systems were reviewed with the patient and included in the chart.
Negative for fecal or urinary incontinence. Negative for abdominal pain. Negative for dyspnea. Negative for fevers, chills, night sweats or unintentional weight loss over the past 3 months. All other 14 Review of Systems are negative unless otherwise stated.
The lumbar spine integument reveals no scars, lesions, rashes or caf√© au lait spots. He has hypersensitivity to light palpation of the lumbar spine and bilateral SI joints.
On physical exam the patient is in no acute distress. Bilateral lower extremity strength is 5 out of 5. Deep tendon reflexes 2+ equal and symmetric. Sensation is intact in all dermatomal distributions. No groin or buttock pain with internal or external rotation of the hips bilaterally. Pedal pulse 2+.
Patient has positive Faber, positive thigh thrust, positive compression,, positive distraction. Gaenslen's was deferred due to the significant pain elicited from physical examination.
Antalgic gait.
1 view AP pelvis ordered, performed and interpreted by myself Dr. Goins in the office today show degenerative change within the SI joints bilaterally. At the hip articulations appear unremarkable.
MRI lumbar spine viewed in epic dated 11/16/2021 read and interpreted by myself and Dr. Goins in the office today show no significant nerve root impingement. There is foraminal stenosis at L3-4 and L4-L5.
Plan: It is my impression the patient is experiencing sacroiliac pain. I recommend diagnostic and therapeutic intra-articular SI injections bilaterally.
Risks and benefits of the injection were reviewed with the patient in detail. They include, but are not limited to, injection site reaction, neurovascular injury, infection, failure to obtain pain relief, increase in pain. The patient conveyed verbal understanding and wishes to proceed.
I will send a referral to his pain management clinic for this treatment.
I conveyed to the patient that other than mild stenosis in his lumbar spine I see no significant neural impingement no significant arthropathy or disc degeneration to correlate with his back pain.
Absolutely no lumbar surgery is indicated.
If he responds favorably to sacroiliac injections I would recommend advanced imaging of the SI joints and we could consider SI fusion.
